# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dns-rebinding-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] This attack can be used to breach a private network by causing the victim's web browser to access computers at private IP addresses and return the results to the attacker.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] It can also be employed to use the victim machine for spamming, distributed denial-of-service attacks, or other malicious activities.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] The attacker registers a domain (such as attacker.com) and delegates it to a DNS server that is under the attacker's control.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] The server is configured to respond with a very short time to live (TTL) record, preventing the DNS response from being cached.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] When the victim browses to the malicious domain, the attacker's DNS server first responds with the IP address of a server hosting the malicious client-side code.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] For instance, they could point the victim's browser to a website that contains malicious JavaScript or Flash scripts that are intended to execute on the victim's computer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] The malicious client-side code makes additional accesses to the original domain name (such as attacker.com).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] These are permitted by the same-origin policy.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] However, when the victim's browser runs the script it makes a new DNS request for the domain, and the attacker replies with a new IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] For instance, they could reply with an internal IP address or the IP address of a target somewhere else on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] Note that DNS filtering conflicts with Domain Name System blocklist.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] RFC 5782 standardizes the use of IP addresses beginning with 127, like 127.0.0.2, for such use.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] Normally, mail servers perform various queries of this kind, either according to local configuration or following external directives, such as the SPF's EXISTS mechanism.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/dns-rebinding] It is crucial for correctness, that mail servers don't utilize DNS servers that perform the above kind of filtering.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] An **Internet Protocol address** (**IP address**) is a numerical label, such as *192.168.1.1* or *2001:0db8:0000:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334*, that is assigned to a device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP addresses serve two main functions: network interface identification, and location addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) was the first standalone specification for the IP address, and has been in use since 1983.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are defined as a 32-bit number, which later then became too small to provide enough addresses as the internet grew, leading to IPv4 address exhaustion over the 2010s.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Its designated successor, IPv6, uses 128 bits for the IP address, giving it a larger address space.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Although IPv6 deployment has been ongoing since the mid-2000s, both IPv4 and IPv6 are still used side-by-side as of 2025.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP addresses are usually displayed in a human-readable notation, but systems may use them in various different computer number formats.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] CIDR notation can also be used to designate how much of the address should be treated as a routing prefix.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] For example, *192.0.2.1/24* indicates that 24 significant bits of the address are the prefix, with the remaining 8 bits used for host addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This is equivalent to the historically used subnet mask (in this case, *255.255.255.0*).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The IP address space is managed globally by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) and the five regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IANA assigns blocks of IP addresses to the RIRs, which are responsible for distributing them to local Internet registries in their region, such as internet service providers (ISPs) and large institutions.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Some addresses are reserved for private networks and are not globally unique.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Within a network, the network administrator assigns an IP address to each device.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Such assignments may be on a *static* (fixed or permanent) or *dynamic* basis, depending on network practices and software features.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the European Union, consider IP addresses to be personal data.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] An IP address serves two principal functions: it identifies the host, or more specifically, its network interface, and it provides the location of the host in the network, and thus, the capability of establishing a path to that host.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Its role has been characterized as follows: "A name indicates what we seek.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A route indicates how to get there." The header of each IP packet contains the IP address of the sending host and that of the destination host.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Two versions of the Internet Protocol are in common use on the Internet today.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The original version of the Internet Protocol that was first deployed in 1983 in the ARPANET, the predecessor of the Internet, is Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] By the early 1990s, the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 address space available for assignment to Internet service providers and end-user organizations prompted the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) to explore new technologies to expand addressing capability on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The result was a redesign of the Internet Protocol, which eventually became known as Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6) in 1995.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv6 technology was in various testing stages until the mid-2000s, when commercial production deployment commenced.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Today, these two versions of the Internet Protocol are in simultaneous use.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Among other technical changes, each version defines the format of addresses differently.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Because of the historical prevalence of IPv4, the generic term *IP address* typically still refers to the addresses defined by IPv4.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The gap in version sequence between IPv4 and IPv6 resulted from the assignment of version 5 to the experimental Internet Stream Protocol in 1979, which, however, was never referred to as *IPv5*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Versions 1 to 9 were defined, but only 4 and 6 ever gained widespread use.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Transmission Control Protocol (the protocol suite later referred to as *TCP/IP*) versions 1 and 2 were published in 1974 and 1977.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Version 3 was defined in 1978, and version 3.1 is the first version in which TCP is separated from IP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Version 6 is a synthesis of several suggested versions, version 6 *Simple Internet Protocol*, version 7 *TP/IX: The Next Internet*, version 8 *P.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Internet Protocol*, and version 9 *TCP and UDP with Bigger Addresses (TUBA)*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP networks may be divided into subnetworks in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] For this purpose, an IP address is recognized as consisting of two parts: the *network prefix* in the high-order bits and the remaining bits called the *rest field*, *host identifier*, or *interface identifier* (IPv6), used for host numbering within a network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The subnet mask or CIDR notation determines how the IP address is divided into network and host parts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The term *subnet mask* is only used within IPv4.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Both IP versions, however, use the CIDR concept and notation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In this, the IP address is followed by a slash and the number (in decimal) of bits used for the network part, also called the *routing prefix*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The CIDR notation for the same IP address and subnet is *192.0.2.1/24*, because the first 24 bits of the IP address indicate the network and subnet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] An IPv4 address has a size of 32 bits, which limits the address space to 4294967296 (232) addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Of this number, some addresses are reserved for special purposes such as private networks (≈18 million addresses) and multicast addressing (≈270 million addresses).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are usually represented in dot-decimal notation, consisting of four decimal numbers, each ranging from 0 to 255, separated by dots, e.g., *192.0.2.1*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Each part represents a group of 8 bits (an octet) of the address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In some cases of technical writing, IPv4 addresses may be presented in various hexadecimal, octal, or binary representations.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In the early stages of development of the Internet Protocol, the network number was always the highest-order octet (most significant eight bits).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Because this method allowed for only 256 networks, it soon proved inadequate as additional networks developed that were independent of the existing networks already designated by a network number.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In 1981, the addressing specification was revised with the introduction of classful network architecture.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Classful network design allowed for a larger number of individual network assignments and fine-grained subnetwork design.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The first three bits of the most significant octet of an IP address were defined as the *class* of the address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Three classes (*A*, *B*, and *C*) were defined for universal unicast addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Depending on the class derived, the network identification was based on octet boundary segments of the entire address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Each class used successively additional octets in the network identifier, thus reducing the possible number of hosts in the higher-order classes (*B* and *C*).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The following table gives an overview of this now-obsolete system.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Classful network design served its purpose in the startup stage of the Internet, but it lacked scalability in the face of the rapid expansion of networking in the 1990s.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The class system of the address space was replaced with Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) in 1993.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] CIDR is based on variable-length subnet masking (VLSM) to allow allocation and routing based on arbitrary-length prefixes.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Today, remnants of classful network concepts function only in a limited scope as the default configuration parameters of some network software and hardware components (e.g. netmask), and in the technical jargon used in network administrators' discussions.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Early network design, when global end-to-end connectivity was envisioned for communications with all Internet hosts, intended that IP addresses be globally unique.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] However, it was found that this was not always necessary as private networks developed and public address space needed to be conserved.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Computers not connected to the Internet, such as factory machines that communicate only with each other via TCP/IP, need not have globally unique IP addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Today, such private networks are widely used and typically connect to the Internet with network address translation (NAT), when needed.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Three non-overlapping ranges of IPv4 addresses for private networks are reserved.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] These addresses are not routed on the Internet, and thus their use need not be coordinated with an IP address registry.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Any user may use any of the reserved blocks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Typically, a network administrator will divide a block into subnets; for example, many home routers automatically use a default address range of *192.168.0.0* through *192.168.0.255* (*192.168.0.0/24*).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In IPv6, the address size was increased from 32 bits in IPv4 to 128 bits, thus providing up to 2128 (approximately 3.403×1038) addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This is deemed sufficient for the foreseeable future.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The intent of the new design was not to provide just a sufficient quantity of addresses, but also to redesign routing in the Internet by allowing more efficient aggregation of subnetwork routing prefixes.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This resulted in slower growth of routing tables in routers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The smallest possible individual allocation is a subnet for 264 hosts, which is the square of the size of the entire IPv4 Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] At these levels, actual address utilization ratios will be small on any IPv6 network segment.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The new design also provides the opportunity to separate the addressing infrastructure of a network segment, i.e., the local administration of the segment's available space, from the addressing prefix used to route traffic to and from external networks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv6 has facilities that automatically change the routing prefix of entire networks, should the global connectivity or the routing policy change, without requiring internal redesign or manual renumbering.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The large number of IPv6 addresses allows large blocks to be assigned for specific purposes and, where appropriate, to be aggregated for efficient routing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] With a large address space, there is no need to have complex address conservation methods as used in CIDR.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] All modern desktop and enterprise server operating systems include native support for IPv6, but it is not yet widely deployed in other devices, such as residential networking routers, voice over IP (VoIP) and multimedia equipment, and some networking hardware.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Just as IPv4 reserves addresses for private networks, blocks of addresses are set aside in IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In IPv6, these are referred to as unique local addresses (ULAs).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The routing prefix *fc00::/7* is reserved for this block, which is divided into two */8* blocks with different implied policies.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The addresses include a 40-bit pseudorandom number that minimizes the risk of address collisions if sites merge or packets are misrouted.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Early practices used a different block for this purpose (*fec0::*), dubbed site-local addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] However, the definition of what constituted a *site* remained unclear and the poorly defined addressing policy created ambiguities for routing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This address type was abandoned and must not be used in new systems.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Addresses starting with *fe80::*, called link-local addresses, are assigned to interfaces for communication on the attached link.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The addresses are automatically generated by the operating system for each network interface.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This provides instant and automatic communication between all IPv6 hosts on a link.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This feature is used in the lower layers of IPv6 network administration, such as for the Neighbor Discovery Protocol.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Private and link-local address prefixes may not be routed on the public Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP addresses are assigned to a host either dynamically as they join the network, or persistently by configuration of the host hardware or software.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Persistent configuration is also known as using a **static IP address**.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In contrast, when a computer's IP address is assigned each time it restarts, this is known as using a **dynamic IP address**.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Dynamic IP addresses are assigned by the network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is the most frequently used technology for assigning addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] It avoids the administrative burden of assigning specific static addresses to each device on a network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] It also allows devices to share the limited address space on a network if only some of them are online at a particular time.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Typically, dynamic IP configuration is enabled by default in modern desktop operating systems.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The address assigned with DHCP is associated with a *lease* and usually has an expiration period.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] If the lease is not renewed by the host before expiry, the address may be assigned to another device.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Some DHCP implementations attempt to reassign the same IP address to a host, based on its MAC address, each time it joins the network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A network administrator may configure a DHCP server to allocate specific IP addresses to specific MAC addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] DHCP is not the only technology used to assign IP addresses dynamically.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Bootstrap Protocol is a similar protocol and predecessor to DHCP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Dialup and some broadband networks use dynamic address features of the Point-to-Point Protocol.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Computers and equipment used for the network infrastructure, such as routers and mail servers, are typically configured with static addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In the absence or failure of static or dynamic address configurations, an operating system may assign a link-local address to a host using stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Address block *169.254.0.0/16* is defined for the special use of link-local addressing for IPv4 networks.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In IPv6, every interface, whether using static or dynamic addresses, also receives a link-local address automatically in the block *fe80::/10*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] These addresses are only valid on the link, such as a local network segment or point-to-point connection, to which a host is connected.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] These addresses are not routable and, like private addresses, cannot be the source or destination of packets traversing the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] When the link-local IPv4 address block was reserved, no standards existed for mechanisms of address autoconfiguration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Filling the void, Microsoft developed a protocol called Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA), whose first public implementation appeared in Windows 98.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] APIPA has been deployed on millions of machines and became a *de facto* standard in the industry.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In May 2005, the IETF defined a formal standard for it.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] An IP address conflict occurs when two devices on the same local physical or wireless network claim to have the same IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A second assignment of an address generally stops the IP functionality of one or both of the devices.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Many modern operating systems notify the administrator of IP address conflicts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] When IP addresses are assigned by multiple people and systems with differing methods, any of them may be at fault.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] If one of the devices involved in the conflict is the default gateway access beyond the LAN for all devices on the LAN, all devices may be impaired.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP addresses are classified into several classes of operational characteristics: unicast, multicast, anycast and broadcast addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The most common concept of an IP address is in unicast addressing, available in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] It normally refers to a single sender or a single receiver, and can be used for both sending and receiving.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Usually, a unicast address is associated with a single device or host, but a device or host may have more than one unicast address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Sending the same data to multiple unicast addresses requires the sender to send all the data many times over, once for each recipient.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Broadcasting is an addressing technique available in IPv4 to address data to all possible destinations on a network in one transmission operation as an *all-hosts broadcast*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] All receivers capture the network packet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In addition, a more limited directed broadcast uses the all-ones host address with the network prefix.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] For example, the destination address used for directed broadcast to devices on the network *192.0.2.0/24* is *192.0.2.255*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv6 does not implement broadcast addressing and replaces it with multicast to the specially defined all-nodes multicast address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A multicast address is associated with a group of interested receivers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In IPv4, addresses *224.0.0.0* through *239.255.255.255* (the former Class D addresses) are designated as multicast addresses.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IPv6 uses the address block with the prefix *ff00::/8* for multicast.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In either case, the sender sends a single datagram from its unicast address to the multicast group address, and the intermediary routers take care of making copies and sending them to all interested receivers (those that have joined the corresponding multicast group).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Like broadcast and multicast, anycast is a one-to-many routing topology.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] However, the data stream is not transmitted to all receivers, just the one that the router decides is closest in the network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Anycast addressing is a built-in feature of IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In IPv4, anycast addressing is implemented with Border Gateway Protocol using the shortest-path metric to choose destinations.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Anycast methods are useful for global load balancing and are commonly used in distributed DNS systems.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A host may use geolocation to deduce the geographic position of its communicating peer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] This is typically done by retrieving geolocation info about the IP address of the other node from a database.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A public IP address is a globally routable unicast IP address, meaning that the address is not an address reserved for use in private networks, such as those reserved by RFC 1918, or the various IPv6 address formats of local scope or site-local scope, for example, for link-local addressing.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Public IP addresses may be used for communication between hosts on the global Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In a home situation, a public IP address is the IP address assigned to the home's network by the ISP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In this case, it is also locally visible by logging into the router configuration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Most public IP addresses change relatively often.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Any type of IP address that changes is called a dynamic IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In home networks, the ISP usually assigns a dynamic IP.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] If an ISP gave a home network an unchanging address, it is more likely to be abused by customers who host websites from home, or by hackers who can try the same IP address over and over until they breach a network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] A common practice is to have a NAT device mask many devices in a private network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Only the public interfaces of the NAT device need to have an Internet-routable address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The NAT device maps different IP addresses on the private network to different TCP or UDP port numbers on the public network.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In residential networks, NAT functions are usually implemented in a residential gateway.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In this scenario, the computers connected to the router have private IP addresses, and the router has a public address on its external interface to communicate on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] The internal computers appear to share one public IP address.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In March 2024, the Supreme Court of Canada decided that the IP addresses are protected private information under the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*, with police searches requiring a warrant in order to obtain them.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] IP addresses are considered personal data by the European Commission and are protected by the *General Data Protection Regulation*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] In the United States, the California Consumer Privacy Act only protects IP addresses that link to any particular consumer or household; otherwise it is not private data and is not protected under American law.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Computer operating systems provide various diagnostic tools to examine network interfaces and address configuration.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/ip-address] Microsoft Windows provides the command-line interface tools ipconfig and netsh and users of Unix-like systems may use ifconfig, netstat, route, lanstat, fstat, and iproute2 utilities to accomplish the task.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] In a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) attack, the attacker can abuse functionality on the server to read or update internal resources.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] The target application may have functionality for importing data from a URL, publishing data to a URL or otherwise reading data from a URL that can be tampered with.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] The attacker modifies the calls to this functionality by supplying a completely different URL or by manipulating how URLs are built (path traversal etc.).
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] When the manipulated request goes to the server, the server-side code picks up the manipulated URL and tries to read data to the manipulated URL.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] The attacker may also use this functionality to import untrusted data into code that expects to only read data from trusted sources, and as such circumvent input validation.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/server-side-request-forgery] See the Server-Side Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] Under the Internet Protocol, TTL is an 8-bit field.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] In the IPv4 header, TTL is the 9th octet of 20.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] In the IPv6 header, it is the 8th octet of 40.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] The maximum TTL value is 255, the maximum value of a single octet.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] The time-to-live value can be thought of as an upper bound on the time that an IP datagram can exist in an Internet system.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] The TTL field is set by the sender of the datagram, and reduced by every router on the route to its destination.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] If the TTL field reaches zero before the datagram arrives at its destination, then the datagram is discarded and an Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) error datagram (11 - Time Exceeded) is sent back to the sender.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] The purpose of the TTL field is to avoid a situation in which an undeliverable datagram keeps circulating on an Internet system, and such a system eventually becoming swamped by such "immortals".
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] In theory, under IPv4, time to live is measured in seconds, although every host that passes the datagram must reduce the TTL by at least one unit.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] In practice, the TTL field is reduced by one on every hop.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] To reflect this practice, the field is renamed *hop limit* in IPv6.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] TTLs also occur in the Domain Name System (DNS), where they are set by an authoritative name server for a particular resource record.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] When a caching (recursive) nameserver queries the authoritative nameserver for a resource record, it will cache that record for the time (in seconds) specified by the TTL.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] If a stub resolver queries the caching nameserver for the same record before the TTL has expired, the caching server will simply reply with the already cached resource record rather than retrieve it from the authoritative nameserver again.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] TTL for NXDOMAIN (non-existent domain) responses is set from the minimum of the MINIMUM field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself, and indicates how long a resolver may cache the negative answer.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] Shorter TTLs can cause heavier loads on an authoritative name server, but can be useful when changing the address of critical services like web servers or MX records, and therefore are often lowered by the DNS administrator prior to a service being moved, in order to reduce possible disruptions.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] An older common TTL value for DNS was 86400 seconds, which is 24 hours.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] A TTL value of 86400 would mean that, if a DNS record was changed on the authoritative nameserver, DNS servers around the world could still be showing the old value from their cache for up to 24 hours after the last update by client.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] Newer DNS methods that are part of a disaster recovery (DR) system may have some records deliberately set extremely low on TTL.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] For example, a 300-second TTL would help key records expire in 5 minutes to help ensure these records are flushed quickly worldwide.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] This gives administrators the ability to edit and update records in a timely manner.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] TTL values are "per record" and setting this value on specific records is sometimes honored automatically by all standard DNS systems worldwide.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] However, a problem persists in that some caching DNS nameservers set their own TTLs regardless of the authoritative records, thus it cannot be guaranteed that all downstream DNS servers have the new records after the TTL has expired.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] Time to live may also be expressed as the date and time on which a record expires.
[src:dns-rebinding-defense/time-to-live] The `Expires:` header in HTTP responses, the `Cache-Control: max-age` header field in both requests and responses and the `expires` field in HTTP cookies express time-to-live in this way.
